---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Mirrored from '../components/Mirrored.astro';
import * as Quickstart from '../mirrored/quickstart.md';
import { DOWNLOAD_ENABLED, RELEASE, RELEASE_TAG, RELEASE_URL, REPO_URL } from '../config';
---
<Base
  title="Get started"
  description="Set up your Executor File: about an hour at the computer, one command at a time. The result is an encrypted register and a printed page your executor can follow forever."
>
  <div class="wrap prose">
    <section class="section">
      <h1>Get started</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        This takes about an hour at the computer, one command at a time, in the
        Terminal. If you can copy and paste, you can do this. The result is an
        encrypted file and a printed page your executor can follow forever.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is the honest shape of it: there is no app, and the Terminal is the
        cost of a tool with nothing behind it that can shut down. Every step
        below tells you what it does before you run it, and nothing is timed.
        When you're ready.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What you need first</h2>
      <p>
        Two small, standard tools: <code>age</code> (encryption) and{' '}
        <code>ssss</code> (secret sharing). Both are free, open source and
        packaged everywhere.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mac:</strong> <code>brew install age ssss</code> (if <code>brew</code> is not found, install it first from <a href="https://brew.sh">brew.sh</a>)</li>
        <li><strong>Ubuntu or Debian Linux:</strong> <code>sudo apt install age ssss</code></li>
        <li><strong>Windows:</strong> the register is created on a Mac or Linux machine; recovery on Windows has <a href="/recover/windows">its own printed sheet</a>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Before anything else, the pre-flight check <code>scripts/doctor.sh</code>
        confirms the tools are present and warns about hazards such as synced
        folders. It changes nothing; it only looks.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="download">
      <h2>Download and unpack</h2>
      {DOWNLOAD_ENABLED ? (
        <>
          <p>
            The download is one compressed file, like a zip, containing the
            folder of scripts and examples. No GitHub account is needed, and
            nothing about the download is tracked by us.
          </p>
          <p>
            <a class="btn btn-primary" href={RELEASE.tarballUrl}>Download Executor File {RELEASE_TAG}</a>
          </p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              Click the button. The file{' '}
              <code>{RELEASE.asset}</code> lands in your Downloads folder.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Mac:</strong> open Downloads in Finder and double-click
              the file. It unpacks itself into a folder called{' '}
              <code>executor-file-{RELEASE_TAG}</code>. That folder is the tool;
              there is nothing to install.
            </li>
            <li>
              Open the <strong>Terminal</strong> app (press{' '}
              <kbd>Cmd</kbd>+<kbd>Space</kbd>, type "Terminal", press return),
              then copy and paste this line and press return:
              <pre tabindex="0"><code>cd ~/Downloads/executor-file-{RELEASE_TAG}</code></pre>
              That points the Terminal at the folder you just unpacked. Every
              command in "The steps" below is run from here.
            </li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            On Ubuntu or Debian Linux, unpack and enter the folder with{' '}
            <code>tar -xzf {RELEASE.asset}</code> then{' '}
            <code>cd executor-file-{RELEASE_TAG}</code>.
          </p>
          <details>
            <summary>Optional: check the download is intact</summary>
            <p>
              In the Terminal, paste{' '}
              <code>shasum -a 256 ~/Downloads/{RELEASE.asset}</code> and press
              return. The long code it prints should match this one, read from
              the <a href={RELEASE_URL}>release assets</a> when this page was
              built:
            </p>
            <pre tabindex="0"><code>{RELEASE.sha256}</code></pre>
            <p>
              If it matches, the file arrived exactly as published. If it does
              not, delete the file and download it again.
            </p>
          </details>
        </>
      ) : (
        <p class="panel">
          The download link goes live with the {RELEASE_TAG} release, together
          with its SHA-256 checksum. Until then the current code is readable in
          full <a href={REPO_URL}>on GitHub</a>.
        </p>
      )}
      <p>
        Your executor never needs this download, or this website. The printed
        instructions use the two standard tools directly.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The steps</h2>
      <p>
        These are the project's own quickstart steps, pulled from the README at
        build time so they can never drift from the code. Run each one in the
        Terminal, from inside the folder you entered above, and read what it
        says before moving on.
      </p>
      <Mirrored file="README.md" label="Quickstart, from the project README">
        <Quickstart.Content />
      </Mirrored>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Then the physical part</h2>
      <p>
        Put one printed share with each of three holders and tell them what it
        is. Store the encrypted file in at least two private places. Print the
        Executor Instructions and store them with the will. The paper matters
        more than the software; the software exists to make the paper true.
      </p>
      <p>
        Questions along the way? The <a href="/faq">FAQ</a> covers the common
        ones, including what happens if a share holder dies.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
